The paper proposes a scheme for approximating kernel functions in sublinear time via random embeddings using structured matrices. This topic is closely related to machine learning and optimization, which are covered by the cs.LG and cs.IT sub-categories. The paper also introduces notions of coherence and graph-theoretic structural constants, which are related to numerical analysis and scientific computing, covered by the cs.NA sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the trade-off between computation and storage requirements, which is relevant to data structures and algorithms, covered by the cs.DS sub-category. Finally, the empirical results support the theory and justify the use of a broader family of structured matrices, which is related to computational complexity and theoretical computer science, covered by the cs.SI sub-category.
